functions.getCodePreviewValue:
function getCodePreviewValue(val) {
  const globalState = this.getRootState()
  const parentPropsValue = this.parent.props.value
  const value = val || (parentPropsValue ?
    this.call('exec', parentPropsValue, this.parent) :
    this.call('exec', this.props.value, this))
  const code = this.call('isObjectLike', value) ?
    value[globalState.framework] || value['symbols'] || value['domql'] :
    value
  if (!code) return
  const stringifiedCode = this.call('isString', code) ?
    code :
    this.call('objectToString', code)
  return this.call('replaceLiteralsWithObjectFields', stringifiedCode)
}
functions.checkFeatureByPackage:
function checkFeatureByPackage(key) {
    const PAGES_PACKAGES_AVAILABILITY_MAP = {
      preview: 0,
      designSystem: 0,
      components: 0,
      integrations: 0,
      settings: 0,
      pages: 0,
      functions: 0,
      state: 0,
      gettingStarted: 0,
      docs: 0,

      colors: 0,
      color: 0,
      media: 0,
      shape: 0,
      typography: 0,
      spacing: 0,
      semantic_color: 0,
      global_themes: 0,
      gradients: 0,
      gradient: 0,
      themes: 0,
      theme: 0,
      icons: 0,
      fonts: 0,
      font: 0,
      cases: 0,

      dependencies: 0,
      secrets: 0,
      content: 0,
      methods: 0,
      snippets: 0,
      files: 0,
      publish: 0
    }

    return (
      Number(this.getRootState()?.package) >= PAGES_PACKAGES_AVAILABILITY_MAP[key]
    )
  }

clients[id].route,/////n        userId: id,/////n        key: clients[id].username,/////n        title: clients[id].username,/////n        src: clients[id].avatar,/////n        isActive: followingUser BorderRadiusBox.code: export default {/////n  extends: 'Flex',/////n  props: (_, s) => ({/////n    borderWidth: '.5px',/////n    borderRadius: /////tilde/////dlrsgn{s.borderStartStartRadius} /////dlrsgn{s.borderStartEndRadius} /////dlrsgn{s.borderEndEndRadius} /////dlrsgn{s.borderEndStartRadius}/////tilde,/////n    borderColor: 'yellow .25',/////n    borderStyle: 'solid',/////n    height: '100%',/////n    onClick: (ev, el, s) => {/////n      const getCornerInputs = () => {/////n        const inputs = [...document.querySelectorAll('input[key="NumberValue"]')];/////n        return inputs.map(input => {/////n          const rect = input.getBoundingClientRect();/////n          return {/////n            el: input,/////n            value: input.value,/////n            x: rect.left + rect.width / 2,/////n            y: rect.top + rect.height / 2,/////n          };/////n        });/////n      }/////n/////n      const corners = getCornerInputs();/////n/////n      let closest = null;/////n      let minDist = Infinity;/////n/////n      for (const c of corners) {/////n        const dx = ev.clientX - c.x;/////n        const dy = ev.clientY - c.y;/////n        const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy);/////n/////n        if (dist < minDist) {/////n          minDist = dist;/////n          closest = c;/////n        }/////n      }/////n/////n      if (closest) {/////n        closest.el.select();/////n      }/////n    },/////n  }),/////n}

P.text: State is defined in the element and can be any type of value. Most often we see states as arrays or objects, although states have inheritance where we can access the closest state from ancestors.
While setting state as string it inherits the value of relevant key inside the parent state.
Triggering state update also invokes element updates, and updates elements values and represented DOM nodes according to state values.
Any component can have state. If state is not applied, element will inherit state from parent or the closes ancestor that has it. Accessing state values can be done within strings and functions.

P.text: What is Symbols?

Symbols is a web-based platform that enables developers to create reusable and consistent UI kits and web projects through an advanced design system. It also allows real-time collaboration between developers, designers, and marketers.
What problem does Symbols solve?

Building reusable UI kits and web projects is difficult, time-consuming, and costly. Symbols provides the most advanced design system out of the box, automating design changes, offering testing/documentation tools, and 500+ ready-to-use components. This makes development up to 10x faster and reduces costs by up to 90%.
What can I build with Symbols?
Anything! From animated landing pages to SaaS apps with charts, APIs, functions, and third-party libraries.
How does my day-to-day workflow look with Symbols?

P1.text: **New project:** Configure design system â†’ Inspect library â†’ Brand components instantly â†’ Build pages â†’ Test & document â†’ Publish/export.

P2.text: **Existing project:** Reconfigure design system for global changes, add new components/pages, and debug with built-in testing tools.

P.text: How can I access Symbols?
Select one of our lifetime offers or book a demo call.
Which frameworks/tech does Symbols support?

Symbols works with React and HTML/CSS, but to unlock full benefits (like layers), use our low-code DOMQL framework. Soon, our compiler will convert DOMQL into other frameworks like React, Vue, Angular, and more.
Is Symbols open source / can I export my code?
The platform itself is closed source, but projects are open. You can export your code at any time for use outside the platform.
Does VS Code work with Symbols?
Yes. You can integrate VS Code via CLI.
Does Symbols support GitHub?
Direct GitHub support is planned, but Symbols already provides faster workflowsâ€”single-click deployment and real-time team sync. Meanwhile, you can always export your code and store it on GitHub.
How does a team collaborate using Symbols?
Symbols includes real-time syncing (like Figma), so teams can see each otherâ€™s changes instantlyâ€”no PR hassle.
Do I need any prior knowledge before starting?
Basic HTML/CSS knowledge is enough to get started. To unlock full potential, learn DOMQLâ€”our low-code JavaScript framework designed for ease of use.

Functions allow you to write reusable frontend and backend functions and call them anytime during your flow. Functions can be used as lambda, self sustaining executable scripts and can be shared across your internal Symbols app or externally with integrations.

Frontend functions can be called within the browser when you want to execute some browser related functionality on your users browser. It can be perfectly used on events such as onClick, onLoad and etc. Most often frontend functions are used to reuse some functionality or wrap API requests in one place.
You can invoke functions from your component from context or with require statement.

children: * Default export only; name = file name in registry.
* Pure functions for frontend (no side effects). Return a value.
* Pass only the data you need; avoid leaking el/DOM refs across layers.
* Prefer async/await for network I/O.
* From any event: onClick, onInput, onStateUpdate, etc.
* Sync (CLI): smbls fetch/push/sync keeps functions in dynamic.json and local files aligned.
* Share: promote to organization library; import in other projects.
* Secrets: keep in Secrets and use backend functions to access.
* Debounce/throttle wrappers for FE functions (search inputs).
* Caching response data (per session) to reduce network calls.
* Streaming/long-running tasks â†’ backend with progress channel (socket).
* Error strategy: always try/catch; return normalized { ok, data, error }.
* Keep FE functions small and pure; test easily.
* Validate arguments; never trust input.
* Use namespaces: ui/*, data/*, auth/*.
* Prefer return values over hidden mutations.
* Log on backend, not frontend, for sensitive info.
* Unit test functions in isolation (Node or browser).
* For components, stub el.call and assert state transitions.
* Use a CI step to run tests before publish.
* Never place tokens in frontend functions.
* Use backend functions to read secrets / call private APIs.
* Enforce RBAC on endpoints; audit logs for sensitive calls.
* Mind CORS for public endpoints.

P.text: Backend functions are running on hosted custom node servers where you can write executable functions that runs on node.js environment. Most often they are used to create safe gateway with integrations where you safely store API keys and make requests to any other third party provider. Backend functions can be called within platform as they are built-in, or by REST API request from any other location.
You can set accessibility options such as Private or Public, as well as set CORS or JWT options to them.

Backend functions require server configuration that runs individual server for your function thats isolated and can handle a specific need to run custom logic. Symbols provides recommended defaults for most use, but you can customize configuration or set to auto scale options. Please be mindful that configuration affects on costs by traffic usage.
Using server functions might add additional cost when exceeding limits included in your current plan. Costs are calculated by usage and traffic and they follow:

DOMQL is a library made by Symbols team to simplify app development process with full potential of reusability and customization. The aim to create this framework was to build one of the most reusable components library, and together with a Design System tools, it creates strong foundation for any frontend development.
Symbols unifies languages to make code management extremely easy. Instead of using different syntax for writing structure, styling and functionality into one syntax.

Text.text: Simple syntax, no compilation or transpiration required

P.text: DOMQL uses Javascript syntax and runs both on Node and Browser without transpirations required. In DOMQL you write your own virtual tree that represents actual website DOM tree after running it in browser.

Text.text: CSS, HTML attributes and component properties, as one object

P.text: With DOMQL and Symbols, you can pass all these given properties as single object. This unified way to interact with component is achieved by passing CSS and HTML attributes alongside with component properties altogether.

DOMQL uses simple javascript syntax and can be run on any Javascript environment. It takes object tree as the first argument and renders website from your original reference. This way you can access your original tree also during lifecycle, log and update it accordingly.
Symbols has more advanced use of DOMQL as it adds on more plugins to make design system and many other features to be integrated in.

P.text: Icons in Symbols are SVGs managed in your Design System and rendered with the Icon component. Add them inline or via Add â†’ Add Icon, then reference by name. They scale cleanly and inherit color from your theme for consistent styling.

Title.text: Paste sanitized SVG into your DS so it becomes available everywhere by name.

children: 1. Keep viewBox (no fixed width/height inside the SVG).
2. Use fill="currentColor" (so you can color it via the color prop).
3. Remove hardcoded fill="#xxxxxx" in paths.

Strong.text: B. Upload via UI (Add â†’ Add Icon):

children: 1. Click + Add Icon
2. Upload an SVG file or paste the SVG text
3. Prefer fill="currentColor" inside the paths
4. Name it in camelCase: heartIcon, arrowVertical, chevronRight

Title_UseInComponent.text: 2. Use an icon in a component

Title_AlternativeUse.text: 3. Alternative: use a raw file with Img

Title.text: File assets can be used instead of DS icons

children: * camelCase: arrowVertical, heartIcon, chevronRight
* Keep names short and semantic
* Suffix variants if needed: heart, heartFilled, heartOutline

P.text: Guides, help, and community resources for working with Symbols.
Quick answers to common questions about Symbols.
Fix common issues and learn how to debug Symbols in your environment.
Ensure that your bundler is configured for both ESM and CommonJS. For older projects, use `require()`; for modern setups, use `import` syntax.
Check that your build pipeline includes CSS-in-JS. Symbols components require style resolution to be part of the bundle.
Make sure your Node.js version is 18+ and that your deployment target supports ES2022 features.
Connect with other developers, share feedback, and get help from the Symbols team.
Expand your knowledge of Symbols and design systems.

DraggableRow.onDragenter:
(e, el, s) => {
    e.preventDefault()
    e.stopPropagation()
    if (!el.parent.data) return
    const isSame = el.parent.data.fromIndex === el.key
    const isSameGroup = el.parent.data.state === s.parent
    const isRootNode = e.target === el.node
    if (isSame || !isSameGroup || isRootNode) return
    el.parent.data.active = el.key
    el.setProps(el.props.dragenter)
  }
DraggableRow.onDragleave:
(e, el, s) => {
    e.preventDefault()
    e.stopPropagation()
    if (!el.parent.data) return
    const isSame = el.parent.data.fromIndex === el.key
    const isSameGroup = el.parent.data.state === s.parent
    const isRootNode = e.target === el.node
    if (isSame || !isSameGroup || isRootNode) return
    el.parent.data.active = el.key
    el.setProps(el.props.dragenter)
  }

Draggable.onDragenter:
(e, el, s) => {
    e.preventDefault()
    e.stopPropagation()
    if (!el.parent.data) return
    const isSame = el.parent.data.fromIndex === el.key
    const isSameGroup = el.parent.data.state === s.parent
    const isRootNode = e.target === el.node
    if (isSame || !isSameGroup || isRootNode) return
    el.parent.data.active = el.key
    el.setProps({
      transform: `scale(0.97)`,
      opacity: '0.9'
    })
  }
Draggable.onDragleave:
(e, el, s) => {
    e.preventDefault()
    e.stopPropagation()
    if (!el.parent.data) return
    const isSame = el.parent.data.fromIndex === el.key
    const isSameGroup = el.parent.data.state === s.parent
    const isRootNode = e.target === el.node
    if (isSame || !isSameGroup || isRootNode) return
    el.parent.data.active = el.key
    el.setProps({
      opacity: '1',
      transform: 'none'
    })
  }
